  "opinion": "As a woman in Bologna who’s been navigating life with three children and a self-employed sales job, I see the gender gap in science not as a distant statistic but as something that affects my daily reality. Growing up in a household where neither parent had a university degree—my dad with a vocational diploma and my mom with just lower secondary education—science wasn’t something we celebrated at home. That’s why I often wonder if the lack of role models in science from my generation made it harder for me to see myself in those fields. I’ve noticed that even in my local community, conversations about science tend to be dominated by men, and when women do participate, they’re often seen as exceptions rather than the norm. But addressing this gap isn’t about fixing something that’s already broken—it’s about creating spaces where everyone feels they belong. For me, it starts with simple things like encouraging girls to explore STEM through hands-on activities at community centers, where they can engage with science without the pressure of formal education. It’s also about listening to women who’ve already entered science and learning from their experiences. I’ve volunteered at a local youth program where I’ve seen how a single conversation about science can spark interest in a child who might otherwise never consider it. The key isn’t to push for more women in science but to make sure that science feels accessible and welcoming to all, regardless of background. In a city like Bologna, where community ties are strong, we can build bridges by supporting local initiatives that bring people together around shared curiosity. The gender gap in science is real, but it’s also solvable—by focusing on inclusion from the ground up.",
